        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-10-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-10-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="57"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d57">
                <head>57. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d57fn1">Source:
                        Central Intelligence Agency, <gloss target="#t_DCI1">DCI</gloss> (<persName
                            corresp="#p_MCJA1">McCone</persName>) Files: Job 80–B01285A, <gloss
                            target="#t_DCI1">DCI</gloss> Mtgs with the <gloss target="#t_Pres1"
                            >Pres</gloss>, Oct-Dec 1964. Top Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-10-16">October 16, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Meeting of an Executive Group of the National Security Council, 16 October
                        1964</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>A special meeting of a small group of members of the National Security
                        Council was convened at the White House at 1030 on 16 October <pb
                            facs="0143" n="109" xml:id="pg_109"/> 1964 to discuss the change of
                        government in Moscow. In attendance were the President, Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                            >McNamara</persName>, Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BGW1"
                            >Ball</persName>, Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_TLE1"
                            >Thompson</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">McGeorge
                            Bundy</persName>, the <gloss target="#t_DCI1">DCI</gloss>, and the
                        undersigned. [Here follows the remainder of paragraph 1 and paragraphs 2–5
                        on other subjects.]</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>During this meeting preliminary reports about the explosion of a nuclear
                        device in Communist China arrived, and there was a good bit of discussion
                        over the kind of statement that should be released from the White House.
                            <persName>Bundy</persName> had a draft of a “stand-by statement” which
                        had been prepared in an interdepartmental committee earlier,<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d57fn2">
                            <persName corresp="#p_RBH1">Read</persName> sent a copy of the draft
                            statement to <persName>Bundy</persName> with a covering memorandum of
                            September 30. (Department of State, Central Files, DEF 12–1 <gloss
                                target="#t_ChiCom1">CHICOM</gloss>) A copy of a draft program of
                            action to minimize the impact of the anticipated Chinese nuclear test,
                            prepared by the interdepartmental committee, is filed with a September
                            25 covering memorandum from <persName>Rostow</persName> to
                                <persName>Bundy</persName>. (Johnson Library, National Security
                            File, Subject File, Nuclear Testing, China)</note> and this was revised
                        during and shortly after the meeting for release,<note n="3" xml:id="d57fn3"
                            >The statement that <persName>Johnson</persName> read to the press at
                            1:20 p.m. that day is printed in <hi rend="italic">Public Papers of the
                                Presidents of the United States: <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Lyndon
                                    B. Johnson</persName>, 1963–64</hi>, Book II, p. 1357.</note>
                        along with the preliminary views provided by JAEIC as to the size and
                        location of the explosion. There was a general discussion of the meaning of
                        the Chinese Communist acquisition of a nuclear capability and a recollection
                        of Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>’s statement of 29
                            September<note n="4" xml:id="d57fn4">For text of <persName
                                corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>’s September 29 statement, see
                            Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, October 19, 1964,
                            pp. 542–543.</note> based upon new data provided by the Intelligence
                        Community concerning the test site that had pretty well prepared the world
                        for expecting this event and not becoming unduly alarmed by it.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CRS1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Ray S. Cline</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <lb/> Deputy Director (Intelligence)</signed>
                </closer>
